Created and initialize WebDriver.
Market it as protected ,so that my child classes can access it like test classes.Basically I am using Inheritance here.
Used @BeforeSuite and @AfterSuite to control test lifecycle setup and teardown.
@BeforeSuite:
It tells TestNG to run this method once, before all tests in the suite.

WebDriverManager.chromedriver().setup();:
This uses WebDriverManager to automatically download and manage the correct version of the ChromeDriver.
Without this, you’d have to manually download and set system properties.

ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions();
Creates an object to customize browser startup behavior.
You can use it to:
run headless, disable popups,and set user agents, etc.

options.addArguments("--remote-allow-origins=*");
This sets a command-line argument for Chrome.
It’s often used to resolve CORS-related issues in local testing or certain security restrictions.
Not always necessary — depends on the app you're testing.

driver.manage().window().maximize();
This command maximizes the browser window.
It helps avoid issues caused by elements being off-screen due to a small window.

navigate to the URL right after the driver starts, ensuring tests start on the correct page.


@AfterSuite
It tells TestNG to run this method once after all tests in the suite have finished running.
It’s used for clean-up operations like closing browser sessions, releasing resources, and logging.

if(driver != null)
This checks if the driver was initialized.
Why? Because if the driver was never set up (e.g. a test failed early), calling driver.quit() on a null driver would throw a NullPointerException.
It’s a safe guard.

driver.quit();
This closes all browser windows and ends the WebDriver session completely.
It also frees up system memory and CPU resources used by ChromeDriver.
This is a best practice — always clean up after tests!

Summary:
In my BaseTest class, I set up the browser before running any test.
I use WebDriverManager to set up ChromeDriver, and then I open the Chrome browser and make the window full screen.
I also use @BeforeSuite, so this setup runs only once before all the tests.
I create the driver as a protected variable so other test classes can use it.
Navigated to url.
At the end, I use @AfterSuite to close the browser after all tests are finished.
This helps keep everything clean and avoids leaving browsers open.